## .NET Performance Analysis — `TimeSpanFormatting.cs`

**Context:** Logging framework, millions of entries/min — all code treated as hot-path.

### Scan Execution Checklist

| Recipe | Hits |
|--------|------|
| `.ToLower()`/`.ToUpper()` | 0 |
| `.ToLowerInvariant()` | 1 |
| `.IndexOf(string)` no `StringComparison` | 0 |
| `.Substring(` | 0 |
| `.StartsWith`/`.EndsWith` no comparison | 0 |
| `.Contains(string)` no comparison | 0 |
| `.Replace(` | 0 |
| `params` | 1 |
| LINQ `.Select`/`.Where`/`.Take`/`.Aggregate` | 12 (excl. comments) |
| `.Any()`/`.All()` | 1 |
| `.ToList()` | 1 |
| `.ToArray()` | 1 (excl. comments) |
| `new List<` | 1 |
| Unsealed classes | 1 of 1 (0%) |
| `sealed class` | 0 |
| Regex / async / HttpClient / JSON | 0 each ✓ |

---

### Findings

#### 1. LINQ Chains on Hot Path (12 instances) 🔴
**Impact:** Each LINQ operator allocates an enumerator + delegate closure. At millions of calls/min, this dominates GC pressure.
**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L128, L140, L143, L146, L149, L158, L169, L244, L261-262, L270-271, L284, L304`

**Fix for `IsContainingOnlyNullValue` (L127-128):** Replace `.Any()` with foreach:
```csharp
private static bool IsContainingOnlyNullValue(List<string?> timeParts)
{
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
        if (part != null) return false;
    return true;
}
```

**Fix for `SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan` (L133-150):** Replace chained `.Where().Take().Where()` + collection expression with a single foreach:
```csharp
private static List<string?> SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan(
    List<string?> timeParts, int precision, bool countEmptyUnits)
{
    var result = new List<string?>(precision);
    int count = 0;
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
    {
        if (count >= precision) break;
        if (countEmptyUnits) { count++; if (part != null) result.Add(part); }
        else if (part != null) { result.Add(part); count++; }
    }
    return result;
}
```

**Fix for `ConcatenateTimeSpanParts` (L155-171):** Accept `List<string?>`, use indexed loop:
```csharp
private static string ConcatenateTimeSpanParts(
    List<string?> timeSpanParts, CultureInfo culture, string collectionSeparator)
{
    var nonNull = new List<string>(timeSpanParts.Count);
    foreach (var part in timeSpanParts)
        if (part != null) nonNull.Add(part);
    // ... rest unchanged with nonNull
}
```

**Fix for `HumanizeDisplayStrings` (L266-272):** Replace `.Select().Where().ToArray()` with foreach:
```csharp
var items = new List<string>(strings is ICollection<string?> c ? c.Count : 4);
foreach (var item in strings)
{
    var trimmed = item?.Trim();
    if (!string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(trimmed))
        items.Add(trimmed!);
}
```

---

#### 2. `enum.ToString().ToLowerInvariant()` — Double Allocation Per Unit (1 instance) 🔴
**Impact:** `enum.ToString()` allocates via reflection + boxing; `.ToLowerInvariant()` allocates again. Called once per time unit per `Humanize()` call — up to 8x per entry at millions/min.
**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L175`
**Fix:** Cache unit names in a static array:
```csharp
private static readonly string[] UnitNames =
[
    "year", "month", "week", "day", "hour", "minute", "second", "millisecond"
];

private static string FormatTimePart(int value, TimeUnit unit, CultureInfo culture)
{
    var unitName = UnitNames[(int)unit];
    return value == 1 ? $"{value} {unitName}" : $"{value} {unitName}s";
}
```

---

#### 3. `params IStringTransformer[]` Array Allocation (1 instance) 🟡
**Impact:** Allocates a `T[]` on every call, even for the common single-transformer case.
**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L303`
**Fix:** Add 1-arg and 2-arg overloads:
```csharp
public static string Transform(this string input, CultureInfo culture,
    IStringTransformer transformer) => transformer.Transform(input);

public static string Transform(this string input, CultureInfo culture,
    IStringTransformer t1, IStringTransformer t2) =>
    t2.Transform(t1.Transform(input));
```

---

#### 4. Unsealed Class `DefaultCollectionFormatter` (1 of 1 = 0% sealed) 🟡
**Impact:** Prevents JIT devirtualization of `virtual` methods (`Humanize` overloads). All 4 virtual methods remain indirect calls.
**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L208`
**Fix:** Add `sealed` keyword — `public sealed class DefaultCollectionFormatter`
**Caveat:** Only if no subclasses exist elsewhere. If subclassing is needed, seal the leaf subclasses instead.

---

#### 5. Double `.Select()` Chain in Object-Formatter Overload (1 instance) 🟡
**Impact:** Two enumerator allocations + two delegate allocations, feeding into `HumanizeDisplayStrings` which adds more.
**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L259-263`
**Fix:** Merge into a single `.Select()`:
```csharp
return HumanizeDisplayStrings(
    collection.Select(item => objectFormatter(item)?.ToString()),
    separator);
```

---

### Positive Findings
- ✅ No `Substring` usage — good
- ✅ No regex — no engine overhead
- ✅ No async anti-patterns
- ✅ No `HttpClient`/`JsonSerializer` issues
- ✅ `List<string?>(8)` in `CreateTimeParts` is pre-sized — good
- ✅ Static `TimeUnits` init is one-time cost (L41) — acceptable

---

### Summary

| Severity | Count | Top Issue |
